    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "Health insurance is the single biggest source of post-divorce financial anxiety for older adults. The rules depend almost entirely on age — specifically, whether each spouse is over or under 65 at the time of divorce.\n\nIf both spouses are 65 or older, the situation is straightforward. Medicare is individual coverage. Each person has their own Medicare card, their own Part A and Part B, and their own Medicare Advantage or Medigap plan. Divorce does not change any of this. The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) confirms at medicare.gov that marital status does not affect Medicare eligibility or premium pricing. You do not need to update anything on Medicare's side after divorce other than your address and emergency contact.\n\nIf one spouse is under 65 and was covered as a dependent on the older spouse's plan (rare, since Medicare does not have spousal dependents the way employer plans do), the younger spouse needs separate coverage. This usually means the Marketplace at healthcare.gov, with subsidies based on the younger spouse's post-divorce income.\n\nThe more common situation is the under-65 spouse on a still-working spouse's employer health plan. This includes federal workers, postal workers, teachers, and many professionals who continue working past traditional retirement age. When divorce is final, the dependent spouse loses employer health coverage. Federal law (COBRA) requires the plan to offer continued coverage for up to 36 months after divorce — longer than the 18 months for job loss. The catch is that COBRA is full price plus a 2 percent administrative fee. A plan that cost the family 400 dollars per month with employer subsidy may cost 1,800 dollars per month on COBRA. The COBRA election period is 60 days after the loss of coverage. Miss it and the option closes permanently.\n\nThe Marketplace at healthcare.gov is the usual landing spot. Divorce qualifies as a Special Enrollment Period under the Affordable Care Act, giving you 60 days to enroll without waiting for the November-December open enrollment window. Subsidies are based on the divorcee's post-divorce income only, not on the household income from before the divorce. This often results in lower-cost coverage than COBRA. Subsidies for those near 65 are generous because premiums climb with age and the ACA caps premium cost as a percentage of income.\n\nIf the younger spouse is 60 or older, the Marketplace covers them only until age 65. At 65 they transition to Medicare. The transition window has its own rules: the Initial Enrollment Period for Medicare starts three months before the 65th birthday, includes the birth month, and continues three months after. Missing this window triggers a late-enrollment penalty that lasts the rest of life. Set a calendar reminder.\n\nMedicare premiums (especially Part B and the income-related monthly adjustment amount, IRMAA) are based on tax return income from two years prior. The divorce year and the year after often produce higher-than-expected Medicare premiums because investment sales, retirement-account splits, and one-time settlements can push income up. SSA Form SSA-44 lets you appeal IRMAA after a life-changing event — and divorce qualifies. Submit the form to your local SSA office with the divorce decree attached.\n\n(Sources: CMS Medicare.gov; U.S. Department of Labor COBRA fact sheet; healthcare.gov Special Enrollment Period rules; SSA Form SSA-44 life-changing event instructions, accessed May 2026)",
