    lastVerifiedAt: "2026-05-09",
    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "The hardest part of divorce after 70 is rarely the money. AARP research from the past decade consistently shows that the long-term struggle is social — the slow reorganization of friendships, family relationships, and daily life that follows a long marriage ending. The financial work has a clear end (the decree is signed). The emotional and social work does not.\n\nFirst, the friendships. Couples in their 30s and 40s tend to maintain individual friendships in parallel with couple friendships. By the 70s, most social contact has consolidated into couple-only friendships built over decades — Friday night dinners with another couple, summer trips with extended families, holiday gatherings at the same houses every year. When the marriage ends, those couple-friendships rarely survive intact. The other couples feel awkward. They may stay closer to one spouse than the other, often the wife. AARP's research finds that within 12 months of a gray divorce, roughly half of pre-divorce friendships have either ended or significantly cooled. This is normal and almost universal. It is not a personal failing.\n\nSecond, the adult children. Children of any age tend to take sides during a parental divorce — but adult children have established loyalties, opinions, and relationships of their own. They are not protected from the conflict the way young children are. Many adult children of divorcing parents report years of awkwardness around holidays, weddings, and grandchildren's events. Some choose sides openly. Some try to stay neutral and feel guilty about it. AARP recommends that divorcing parents have a single, calm conversation with each adult child early in the process, without blaming the other spouse, and accept that the children will process the news on their own timeline.\n\nThird, the grandchildren. If grandchildren are old enough to understand, they may have a hard time. Patterns of grandparent visits that were built around couple-time often need to be rebuilt one-on-one. This is actually an opportunity — individual grandparent time often deepens relationships in ways the couple version did not — but it takes new planning and new traffic patterns.\n\nFourth, the daily routine. Long marriages create deep daily patterns: who cooks, who handles the bills, who calls the doctor, who buys the groceries, who takes the trash out. After divorce, every one of these has to be re-learned for one person. AARP's gray divorce guides recommend writing down a daily and weekly checklist for the first 60 days — the structure helps with the disorientation that follows the loss of a spouse-shaped daily life.\n\nFifth, the dating question. About one-third of older adults divorced after 60 do eventually re-partner or remarry, according to Pew Research data. The other two-thirds do not. Both paths are normal. Online dating apps for adults 50+ (OurTime, SilverSingles, Match) have grown rapidly. Pace is important: AARP recommends waiting at least 12 months after the decree before serious dating, both for emotional clarity and to avoid making decisions about a new partnership that are really about loneliness.\n\nFinally, grief. The end of a long marriage produces real grief, even when both spouses wanted it. The grief is for the years invested, the future imagined together, the version of yourself that was a married person. Therapists who specialize in life transitions, support groups through AARP or community senior centers, faith communities, and individual mentors all help. The grief is not a problem to be solved. It is a process to be lived through. Most older adults report that the second year is meaningfully better than the first.\n\n(Sources: AARP Sex, Romance & Relationships research; Pew Research Center divorce and remarriage data; American Association for Retired Persons gray divorce guides; National Council on Aging social isolation resources, accessed May 2026)",
